Differences

Interview Questions:

1. Differentiate between Collection and Collections?
-->
| Collection                                            | Collections                               |
| ----------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| `Collection` is an interface.                         | `Collections` is a utility class.         |
| It is the root interface of the Collection Framework. | Provides utility methods for collections. |
| Implemented by List, Set, Queue, etc.                 | Contains only static methods.             |
| Package: `java.util`                                  | Package: `java.util`                      |

Example :

    Collection :
        Collection<String> c = new ArrayList<>();
        c.add("Java");

    
    Collections :
        Collections.sort(list);
        Collections.reverse(list);
        Collections.shuffle(list);
        Interview Tip
        Collection → Interface
        Collections → Utility Class



2. Differentiate between Iterable and Iterator?
-->
| Iterable                                                     | Iterator                                     |
| ------------------------------------------------------------ | -------------------------------------------- |
| Interface that represents a collection that can be iterated. | Interface used to iterate over a collection. |
| Contains `iterator()` method.                                | Contains `hasNext()`, `next()`, `remove()`.  |
| Used in enhanced for-loop.                                   | Used to access elements one by one.          |
| Implemented by Collection classes.                           | Returned by `iterator()` method.             |

Example :
    List<String> list = List.of("A","B","C");
    
    Iterator<String> it = list.iterator();
    
    while(it.hasNext()){
        System.out.println(it.next());
    }


  Interview Tip :
      Iterable → Gives an Iterator
      Iterator → Traverses elements



3. Differentiate between an Array and an ArrayList?
-->
| Array                            | ArrayList                                            |
| -------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------- |
| Fixed size                       | Dynamic size                                         |
| Can store primitives and objects | Stores only objects (wrapper classes for primitives) |
| Faster                           | Slightly slower                                      |
| No built-in methods              | Rich API (`add()`, `remove()`, `contains()`)         |
