9. Differentiate between Queue and Stack?
-->
| Queue                              | Stack                            |
| ---------------------------------- | -------------------------------- |
| FIFO (First In First Out)          | LIFO (Last In First Out)         |
| Insertion at rear                  | Insertion at top                 |
| Deletion from front                | Deletion from top                |
| Uses `offer()`, `poll()`, `peek()` | Uses `push()`, `pop()`, `peek()` |
| Example: LinkedList, PriorityQueue | Example: Stack, ArrayDeque       |

      Queue Example :
          Queue<Integer> queue = new LinkedList<>();
          
          queue.offer(10);
          queue.offer(20);
          
          System.out.println(queue.poll());
      
      Output :
          10
      
      Stack Example
          Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();
          
          stack.push(10);
          stack.push(20);
          
          System.out.println(stack.pop());
      
      Output :
          20
      
      Interview Tip :
          Queue → FIFO
          Stack → LIFO


10. Differentiate between PriorityQueue and TreeSet?
-->
| PriorityQueue                   | TreeSet                                         |
| ------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------- |
| Queue implementation            | Set implementation                              |
| Allows duplicate elements       | Does not allow duplicates                       |
| Sorted according to priority    | Sorted according to natural order or Comparator |
| Only head element is guaranteed | Entire collection remains sorted                |
| Implements Queue                | Implements NavigableSet                         |

    Example :
    
    PriorityQueue :
        PriorityQueue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<>();
        
        pq.add(30);
        pq.add(10);
        pq.add(20);
        
        System.out.println(pq.poll());
    
    Output :
        10
    
    TreeSet :
        TreeSet<Integer> set = new TreeSet<>();
        
        set.add(30);
        set.add(10);
        set.add(20);
        
        System.out.println(set);
    
    Output :
        [10, 20, 30]
    
    
    Interview Tip :
        PriorityQueue → Priority-based processing
        TreeSet → Sorted unique elements
    



11. Differentiate between the Singly Linked List and Doubly Linked List?
-->
| Singly Linked List            | Doubly Linked List                               |
| ----------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------ |
| One pointer (`next`)          | Two pointers (`prev`, `next`)                    |
| Forward traversal only        | Forward and backward traversal                   |
| Less memory                   | More memory                                      |
| Simpler implementation        | More complex implementation                      |
| Faster insertion at beginning | Easier deletion when node reference is available |

    Structure
      Singly Linked List :
          10 → 20 → 30 → null  
    
    Doubly Linked List :
          null ← 10 ⇄ 20 ⇄ 30 → null
          
    Interview Tip :
          Singly → One Direction
          Doubly → Two Directions


      
12. Differentiate between Iterator and Enumeration?
-->
| Iterator                                   | Enumeration                                   |
| ------------------------------------------ | --------------------------------------------- |
| Introduced in Collection Framework         | Legacy interface                              |
| Works with all collections                 | Mainly used with Vector and Hashtable         |
| Can remove elements                        | Cannot remove elements                        |
| Methods: `hasNext()`, `next()`, `remove()` | Methods: `hasMoreElements()`, `nextElement()` |
| Preferred in modern Java                   | Rarely used today                             |


      
      Iterator Example
            Iterator<String> it = list.iterator();
            
            while(it.hasNext()){
                System.out.println(it.next());
            }
      Enumeration Example
            Vector<String> vector = new Vector<>();
            
            Enumeration<String> e = vector.elements();
            
            while(e.hasMoreElements()){
                System.out.println(e.nextElement());
            }
      Interview Tip
            Iterator → Modern + Remove Supported
            Enumeration → Legacy + Read-only



