20. Differentiate between Fail-Fast Iterator and Fail-Safe Iterator?
-->. A fail-fast iterator does not allow you to change (add or remove) elements of a list directly while iterating over it. If you do,
it will immediately throw a ConcurrentModificationException to prevent unpredictable errors.

| Fail-Fast Iterator                       | Fail-Safe Iterator                                   |
| ---------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------- |
| Throws `ConcurrentModificationException` | Does not throw `ConcurrentModificationException`     |
| Iterates over the original collection    | Iterates over a copy of the collection               |
| Faster                                   | Slightly slower                                      |
| Used by most collection classes          | Used by concurrent collections                       |
| Example: `ArrayList`, `HashMap`          | Example: `CopyOnWriteArrayList`, `ConcurrentHashMap` |

Fail-Fast Example
ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<>();

list.add("Java");
list.add("Python");

for(String s : list){
    list.add("Spring");   // ConcurrentModificationException
}
Fail-Safe Example
CopyOnWriteArrayList<String> list = new CopyOnWriteArrayList<>();

list.add("Java");

for(String s : list){
    list.add("Spring");   // No Exception
}
Interview Tip
Fail-Fast → Detects modification
Fail-Safe → Works on a copied collection



21. Differentiate between Iterator and Spliterator?
-->
| Iterator                       | Spliterator                            |
| ------------------------------ | -------------------------------------- |
| Introduced in Java 1.2         | Introduced in Java 8                   |
| Sequential traversal           | Sequential and parallel traversal      |
| One element at a time          | Can split elements into multiple parts |
| Used in Collections            | Used mainly in Streams                 |
| Methods: `hasNext()`, `next()` | Methods: `tryAdvance()`, `trySplit()`  |

