sp.forEachRemaining(System.out::println);
Interview Tip
Iterator → Sequential traversal
Spliterator → Parallel processing (Java 8 Streams)



22. Difference between WeakHashMap and IdentityHashMap?
-->
| WeakHashMap                                                   | IdentityHashMap                             |
| ------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------- |
| Uses **weak references** for keys                             | Uses **reference equality (`==`)** for keys |
| Entries can be removed automatically by the Garbage Collector | Entries remain until explicitly removed     |
| Uses `equals()` for comparison                                | Uses `==` (reference comparison)            |
| Useful for caches and memory-sensitive applications           | Useful when object identity matters         |
| Implements `Map`                                              | Implements `Map`                            |


WeakHashMap Example
WeakHashMap<String, String> map = new WeakHashMap<>();

String key = new String("Java");

map.put(key, "Programming");

key = null;

System.gc();

The entry may be removed after garbage collection if no strong reference to the key exists.

IdentityHashMap Example
IdentityHashMap<String, Integer> map = new IdentityHashMap<>();

String s1 = new String("Java");
String s2 = new String("Java");

map.put(s1, 1);
map.put(s2, 2);

System.out.println(map.size());

Output

2

Although s1.equals(s2) is true, they are different objects (s1 != s2), so IdentityHashMap treats them as different keys.

Interview Tip
WeakHashMap → Keys can be garbage collected
IdentityHashMap → Compares keys using ==, not equals()



